ers a narrative of Jewish history from the inside out, bringing to light the various divisions and rivalries within the Jewish community. This approach, in turn, allows for a deeper understanding of the complex relations between Spanish Jews and their Muslim and Christian neighbors. Jonathan Ray’s original perspective on the Jewish experience is particularly instructive when considering the widescale anti-Jewish riots of 1391. The combination of violence and mass conversion of the Jews irrevocably shifted the dynamics of inter-religious relations as well as those within the Jewish community itself. Yet even in the wake of these tragic events, the Jews of Spain continued to flourish, fostering a culture that they would carry into exile and that would preserve the memory of Jewish Spain for centuries to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aJewszSpainxCivilization. 0aJewszSpainxHistory. 0aMiddle Ages. 4aHistory of Jewish People and Culture. 4aHistory-Europe. 4aHistory-Medieval 500 to 1500. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  a1391 massacre.  a1492.  aAl-Andalus.  aCastile.  aChristian rule.  aConversos.  aCrown of Aragon.  aIberia.  aInquisition.  aJewish Spain.  aJewish history.  aMedieval Spain.  aMuslim rule.  aSepharad.  aSephardic Jews.  aSephardim.  ablack death.  adaily life.  aexile.  aexpulsion.  afifteenth century.  afourteenth century.  akabbalah.  amass conversion.  aplague.  apogrom.  apoverty.  ariots.  asocial history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079137240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9781512823844?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512823844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781512823844/origin